\section{Potential Distribution Inside the Channel}

Consider Fig. \ref{Fig:3.1}, at $V_{ds}$ $>$ 0V, the drain current density, $J_d$ inside SiC MESFET channel is given by $J_d = qN_d{\upsilon}$, where $\upsilon$ is the low field velocity. The channel current can be defined as \cite{Ladbrooke1989}
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:3.4}
I_d=qN_d{\upsilon}W\left[a-h_x\right]~,
\end{equation}
where $W[a-h_x]$ is the available channel cross-section for the flow of current as shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:3.1}, $q$ is the electronic charge, $a$ represents epi-layer thickness and $h_x$ represents depletion layer height at any point $x$. For low field regions, $\beta$ can be substituted as unity in \eqref{Eq:3.3} and combining it with \eqref{Eq:3.4} yields
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:3.5}
I_d=qN_d\left(\frac{{\mu }_0E\left(x\right)}{1+\left[{\mu }_0E\left(x\right)/\upsilon_s\right]}\right)W\left(a-h_x\right)~.
\end{equation}
or
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:3.7}
I_d\left(1+\frac{{\mu }_0}{\upsilon_s}\frac{dV\left(x\right)}{dx}\right)=qN_d{\mu }_0W\frac{dV\left(x\right)}{dx}\left(a-h_x\right)~.
\end{equation}
Since depletion height underneath the Schottky barrier gate at point $x$ is given by \cite{Ladbrooke1989},
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:3.8}
{h^2_x}=\frac{2{\varepsilon}_s}{qN_d}\left[V\left(x\right)-V_g+V_{bi}\right]~,
\end{equation}
where $\varepsilon_s$ is the permittivity of SiC, $V_g$ is the gate biasing, $V_x$ is the potential at any point $x$ because of the drain biasing and $V_{bi}$ is the built-in potential. From the above expression, $2h_x dh_x = [2\varepsilon_s/qN_d]dV(x)$ and substituting the same in \eqref{Eq:3.7} gives
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:3.9}
\begin{aligned}
I_d\left(dx+\frac{{\mu }_0}{\upsilon_s}\frac{qN_d}{{\varepsilon}_s}h_xdh_x\right)
=qN_d{\mu}_0W\frac{qN_d}{{\varepsilon }_s}h_x\left(a-h_x\right)dh_x~.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
Integrating both sides with appropriate limits as per the geometry of Fig. \ref{Fig:3.1}:
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:3.10}
\begin{aligned}
I_d\left(\int^{L_g}_0{dx}+\frac{qN_d{\mu }_0}{\upsilon_s{\varepsilon }_s}\int^{h_d}_{h_0}{h_xdh_x}\right)=\frac{\left(qN_d\right)^2 \mu_0W}{\varepsilon_s}\int^{h_d}_{h_0}{h_x\left(a-h_x\right)dh_x}~.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
or
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:3.11}
\begin{aligned}
I_d\left[L_g+\frac{qN_d{\mu }_0a^2}{2v_s{\varepsilon }_s}\left(\frac{h^2_d}{a^2}-\frac{h^2_0}{a^2}\right)\right]=\frac{{\left(qN_d\right)}^2{\mu }_0W}{6{\varepsilon }_s}a^3\ \left[3\left(\frac{h^2_d}{a^2}-\frac{h^2_0}{a^2}\right)-2\left(\frac{h^3_d}{a^3}-\frac{h^3_0}{a^3}\right)\right]~.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
The normalized depletion layer width, by using \eqref{Eq:3.8} at source, $u_0$ and drain, $u_d$ edges of the gate can be expressed respectively as,
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:3.12}
u_0=\frac{h_0}{a}=\frac{1}{a}\sqrt{\frac{2{\varepsilon }_s\left[V_{bi}-V_g\right]}{qN_d}}~.
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
\label{Eq:3.13}
u_d=\frac{h_d}{a}=\frac{1}{a}\sqrt{\frac{2{\varepsilon }_s\left[V_{bi}-V_g+V_d\right]}{qN_d}}~.
\end{equation}
Consider a submicron SiC MESFET whose device variables are defined in Table \ref{Tab:3.2}. For this device the depletion layer height, before the onset of current saturation, has been plotted by using \eqref{Eq:3.13} and shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:3.3}. It is obvious from the figure that with increasing magnitude of $V_g$, the depletion layer terminates at lower $V_d$ values because, it is linked with saturation drain voltage, $V_{d(sat)}$, which itself is dependent on $V_g$. Since the depletion layer is normalized with physical channel thickness ($a$), its value below unity indicates that for given $V_g$ biasing, a finite thickness of physical channel is still available for the conduction of current. Thus, current saturation in submicron SiC MESFET is caused by the velocity saturation of the carriers contrary to long channel devices where current saturation is associated with the channel pinch-off \cite{Ladbrooke1989}. Substituting $u_0$ and $u_d$ from \eqref{Eq:3.12} and \eqref{Eq:3.13} in Eqn. \eqref{Eq:3.11} and rearranging for $I_d$, we get

